2. Build — the CRT view (match existing components)
Add a "Collaborative Red Teaming" entry to the Policy UI navigation, with two screens:

2a. Campaigns list

Table of campaigns: name/id, target, status (recruiting/active/completed), participating-org count, coverage %, created date. Reuse the existing table/list component.

2b. Campaign detail

Coverage map: the 6 DAO leaves as tiles/rows — covered vs. not, best score, severity badge. Reuse the leaf ids from DAO_TAXONOMY (same as the fine-tuning seed set) — do not hardcode a divergent list.
Metrics strip: coverage fraction, org-type diversity, participating-org count, total credits.
CRTReport panel: pretty-printed report JSON + report_hash (from src/crypto/canonical.py digest()), with a "ZK proof: pending" badge (the zk_proof_hex seam).
Privacy invariant, made visible: show the public coverage (leaf → covered/score, no org) prominently; if you show attribution at all, it must be a clearly separate, operator-only panel — never inline in the public coverage. Add a caption: "coverage is public; attribution is private."
Optional (product call): a "Siloed vs Collaborative" comparison banner mirroring the demo, to make the value legible. Mark it clearly as illustrative if data is simulated.


3. Backend — minimal read API (only if not already present)
Following the repo's existing server pattern, add read-only GET routes that serialize the src/crt MVP (in-memory is fine for the spike):

GET /crt/campaigns → list
GET /crt/campaigns/{id} → campaign + metrics
GET /crt/campaigns/{id}/coverage → CoverageMap (must contain no org_id — verify)
GET /crt/campaigns/{id}/report → CRTReport incl. report_hash Campaign creation can stay CLI-driven for the spike (python -m crt.cli demo); the UI is read/monitor. Mark write/aggregation/x402/ClickHouse hooks as # A.5-full: TODOs.


4. Fixture fallback (so the UI demos without the API)
Ship crt_sample_report.json (a finalized demo campaign: 6/6 covered, 3 orgs, diversity 0.75, a hash). The view loads live data if the API responds, else falls back to the fixture with a small "sample data" badge. This keeps the UI demoable in parallel with backend work.


5. Privacy invariant (verify in the UI layer too)
The coverage payload the UI renders publicly contains no org identity (assert 'org_id' not in coverageResponse). Add a test/lint that fails if an org field leaks into the public coverage component's props.


6. Tests / Verify
Component renders campaigns list + detail from the fixture.
Coverage map shows all 6 leaves with correct covered/score; metrics compute from the report.
Public coverage component receives no org attribution (privacy test).
If routes added: GET /crt/campaigns/{id}/coverage returns no org_id.

